ontiers that medieval romances imagine and imply, but also more metaphorical demarcations. It is these boundaries, as they appear in insular romances circulating in English and French, which the essays in this volume address. They include the boundary between reality and fictionality; boundaries between different literary traditions, modes and cultures; and boundaries between different kinds of experience or perception, especially the "altered states" associated with sickness, magic, the supernatural, or the divine. CONTRIBUTORS: HELEN COOPER, ROSALIND FIELD, MARIANNE AILES, PHILLIPA HARDMAN, ELIZABETH BERLINGS, SIMON MEECHAM-JONES, ELIZABETH WILLIAMS, ARLYN DIAMOND, ROBERT ROUSE, LAURA ASHE, JUDITH WEISS, IVANA DJORDJEVIC, CORINNE SAUNDERS  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aRomancesxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMedieval romance.  aUlrich von Hutten.  aaltered states.  aarchitecture.  aboundaries.  acultures.  adivine.  afictionality.  afine arts.  afolklore.  ainsular romances.  aliberal arts.  aliterary traditions.  amagic.  amineralogy.  amodes.  aprint media.  areality.  asickness.  asupernatural.  atheatrical improvisation.1 aAiles, Marianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshe, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlings, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartlidge, Neil M.R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCartlidge, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiamond, Arlyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDjor